Method Detail

getOpenedIcon

public Image getOpenedIcon()
obtain an additional icon that represents an open Folder, for use with Catalog. It should optimally be 15x15 pixels. The icon provided by getIcon() will be used to represent a closed Folder.

See Also:
Content.getIcon()

hasContent

public boolean hasContent()
determine if this folder has children or otherwise. Normally, this method will return true, however, some special cases of Folders may require a long transacton to determine the initial contents and should initially return false. A user interface such as the Catalog might choose to initially display this Folder as a "leaf" node instead of as a folder node - an example of this are the folders that represent ArcIMS4 services. After opening an ArcIMS 4 web site in the Catalog, each service is initially displayed as a "disconnected" icon. After the end-user double-clicks the icon, the getContents() method is invoked, and eventually the children of the folder are displayed - typically the Layers available within that service.

See Also:
Catalog

getContents

public Content[] getContents()
                      throws IOException
obtain all the Content objects within this Folder. Calling this method will normally cause the Folder to query external data and rebuild the list of Content objects.

Returns:
an array of Contents, empty array if none were found
Throws:
IOException - if any problem while attempting to access the Contents

refresh

public void refresh()
             throws IOException
refresh this Folder's idea of its Contents. For a Folder that caches its Contents, this method provides a way to reconnect with the external folder and update its cache. For other Folders, this method should do nothing.
